            <subject>Re: Slide 22: Deadbeat Estimator</subject>
            <message>&lt;p&gt;The word deadbeat came from the controller design.  A deadbeat controller is one that follows the setpoint exactly and immediately.  For the controller to behave like this, we need the controller to be the fastest, which mathematically translates into the poles of the controller being at the origin - please see the book for an example of a deadbeat controller.  The same logic is used in the coining of this term for the estimator.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The deadbeat estimator may be susceptible to noise, just as the output feedback controller is.  On the other hand, it is possible to smoothen the measurement by properly designing an estimator.  An optimally designed estimator is called the Kalman Filter.&lt;/p&gt;</message>
            <messageformat>1</messageformat>
